<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="544" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1128,1676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1128,1153]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">Description.</emphasis>
The male of this species was originally described by Inoue (
<number box="[1046,1104,1129,1153]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="1978.0">1978</number>
) and recently redescribed by Han and Xue (
<number box="[313,375,1163,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="2009.0">2009</number>
). Chang (
<number box="[481,539,1163,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="1991.0">1991</number>
) illustrated both sexes. Here the description of female genitalia is given. Female (
<figureCitation box="[159,240,1197,1222]" captionStart="FIGURE 9 – 16" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1846,1868]" captionTargetBox="[264,1321,198,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[252,1336,193,1825]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 9 – 16. Habitus of Hemistola spp. in Taiwan and Japan. 9. H. kezukai Inoue, 1978, male; 10. ditto, female; 11. H. orbiculosa, male; 12. ditto, female; 13. H. simplex Warren, 1899, male; 14. H. taiwanensis sp. nov., male, holotype; 15. H. tenuilinea (Alphéraky, 1897), male; 16. ditto, female; 9 – 14. Taiwan; 15 – 16. Japan; 10 – 12. Photo before abdomen dissected. Bar scale = 10 mm. Specimens courtesy of: TFRI (9 – 14); NSMT (15 – 16). Photo by Shipher Wu." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219250/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">
Fig. 
<number box="[211,240,1198,1222]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
) Wingspan 
<quantity box="[374,473,1197,1222]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.55" metricValueMax="3.6" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" unit="m" value="35.5" valueMax="36.0" valueMin="35.0">35–36 m</quantity>
(n= 
<number box="[526,543,1198,1222]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="4.0">4</number>
). Head: Antenna filiform, ramus slightly longer than diameter of antennal shaft. Frons and labial palpus dark reddish brown. Vertex bluish green, anterior margin white. Labial palpus slender. Thorax: Three segments of thorax bluish green. Wings:Wing ground coloration bluish green; transversal lines white, dentate with red spot on each vein; outer margin rufous; marginal scales cream white with rufous at end of each vein. Forewing apex pointed; costal margin ochreous; discal spot small, dark green. Hindwing with discal spot dark green; outer margin strongly protruded at end of M 
<number box="[779,787,1386,1400]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="3.0">3</number>
. Abdomen: Abdomen bluish green with dorsal white spot surrounding with reddish scales at dorsal part of each segment. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1082,1168,1408,1433]" captionStart="FIGURE 43 – 49" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1916,1938]" captionTargetBox="[293,1285,298,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[281,1305,289,1894]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 43 – 49. Female genitalia of Hemistola spp. in Taiwan and Japan. 43. H. piceacola sp. nov.; 44. H. fui sp. nov.; 45. H. monotola Inoue, 1983; 46. H. kezukai Inoue, 1978; 47. H. orbiculosa Inoue, 1978; 48. H. simplex Warren, 1899; 49. H. tenuilinea (Alphéraky, 1897); 43 – 48. Taiwan; 49. Japan. Bar scale = 1 mm. Specimens courtesy of: TFRI (43 – 48); NSMT (49). Photo by Shipher Wu." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219254/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">
Fig. 
<number box="[1135,1168,1408,1433]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="46.0">46</number>
</figureCitation>
): Lamella postvaginalis sclerotized, especially at posterior part; ductus bursae extremely short; basal half part of corpus bursae gradually widen, sclerotized dorsally, slightly scobinated ventrally, distal half part round, membernous; appendix bursae membranous, small sac-like, arising from ventral, basal part of corpus bursae; ductus seminalis arising at end of appendix bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="544" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1128,1676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,539,1581,1606]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">Distribution and Bionomics.</emphasis>
This species was originally described from 
<collectingCountry box="[1044,1126,1581,1606]" name="Taiwan" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
and subsequently recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[180,247,1616,1641]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="544">China</collectingCountry>
(Shaanxi, Gansu, Guangxi, 
<quantity box="[564,713,1616,1641]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.375" metricValueMax="1.65" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" unit="m" value="1375.0" valueMax="1650.0" valueMin="1100.0">1100–1650m</quantity>
) (Han and Xue, 
<number box="[900,961,1617,1641]" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" value="2009.0">2009</number>
). The Taiwanese population occurs in mid elevations (ca. 
<quantity box="[319,479,1651,1676]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="6" pageNumber="544" unit="m" value="2000.0" valueMax="2400.0" valueMin="1600.0">1600–2400 m</quantity>
). The adults fly in summer, and are possibly univoltine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
